<dl id="n53049d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53049d">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53049d"> 49(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> two = thou / tat tvam asi / = thou art it too <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53049d"><li>FW 601.11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/lexta.htm#n53049d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/l39ta.htm#n53049d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53049d">MS BL 47488-33v</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:054 <a name="tad3" href="../../ff/fdra/tda.htm#tad3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ta/tad3.htm#n53049d">Draft: IV&sect;1.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[It would be nice if originally the number &lsquo;<mark>two</mark>&rsquo; (frequently <i>tva</i> or <i>dva</i>) and the pronoun &lsquo;<mark>thou</mark>&rsquo; would have been one and the same word &hellip; In that case, a long time ago, the famous sentence from the Vedas &mdash; <mark>Tat tvam asi</mark> &mdash; really would have meant: &lsquo;<mark>Thou art my second self</mark>&rsquo;]</font> <small> Fritz Mauthner, <a name="FMBK1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FMBK1"><cite title="source">Beitr&auml;ge zu einer Kritik der Sprache.</cite></a> 3 vols (1901-2) III 182</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: In many languages the words &lsquo;two&rsquo; and &lsquo;thou&rsquo; are cognate. The Sanskrit phrase <i>Tat-tvam-asi</i> [from the Chandogya Upanishad] &mdash; That Thou Art &mdash; reveals the interconnectedness between the Brahma (the That) and the individual (the Thou). <i>Tat-tva</i> means &lsquo;That which actually is&rsquo; and can be resolved into the elements <i>tat</i> and <i>tvam</i> meaning That and Thou, which (ahem!) more concisely expresses the same idea. </mm> </dd></dl>
